{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13565"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13565"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.18,0.05,0.66,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108348"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"657"},{"type":"tags","id":"702"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11637"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108348"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department in the middle of the night with severe neck pain, difficulty swallowing, and progressive swelling of the floor of the mouth. He is unable to speak properly. His wife reports that he had a dental infection that started a few days ago, which he attempted to manage with over-the-counter pain medications. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient appears anxious and is drooling profusely. His blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg, pulse 120/min, temperature 39.5\u00b0C, respiratory rate 26/min, and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 92% on room air. On intraoral examination, there is notable swelling in the floor of the mouth with a woody induration and elevation of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan of the neck without contrast shows diffuse swelling of the submandibular and sublingual spaces without abscess formation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the pathophysiological mechanism leading to this patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct haematogenous spread of infection to the lymph node","Obstruction of the submandibular salivary gland ducts leading to sialadenitis","Primary viral infection of the submandibular and sublingual glands","Rapid spread of bacterial infection through the fascial planes of the neck","Autoimmune reaction causing inflammation of the submandibular region"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has developed Ludwig\u0027s angina. Ludwig\u0027s angina is a term used to describe a rapidly spreading bacterial infection in the floor of the mouth which is most often due to a dental infection. Untreated, the infection can progress rapidly and spread into the submandibular and sublingual spaces of the neck. The initial dental infection, possibly from a lower molar, provides a portal of entry for oral flora, including anaerobic bacteria like group A Streptococcus species, Staphylococcus, Fusobacterium, and Bacteroides species, which are commonly implicated in such infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient\u0027s underlying condition of type 2 diabetes may have compromised his immune response, increasing susceptibility to severe infections. In Ludwig\u0027s angina, the \u003Cstrong\u003Einfection rapidly progresses through the loose connective tissue and fascial planes of the neck\u003C/strong\u003E, causing profound swelling, pain, and potential airway obstruction due to compression of vital structures. The lack of abscess formation on the CT scan suggests diffuse cellulitis rather than localised purulent collection. Prompt recognition and aggressive management with broad-spectrum antibiotics, airway support if necessary, and potential surgical intervention are crucial to prevent complications and ensure patient recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect haematogenous spread of infection to the lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E can cause lymphadenitis and systemic infection, it does not typically cause localised swelling and induration of the submandibular and sublingual spaces as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialadenitis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the salivary glands, typically due to duct obstruction, leading to gland swelling, pain, and sometimes infection. This condition can cause pain and swelling in the affected gland but is less likely to cause the severe, diffuse neck swelling, woody induration, and tongue elevation described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary viral infections of the submandibular and sublingual glands,\u003C/strong\u003E such as mumps, can cause gland swelling and pain. However, they typically do not present with such rapid progression, severe systemic symptoms, or the diffuse, severe neck swelling described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune diseases\u003C/strong\u003E can cause gland inflammation, such as in Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome. Autoimmune inflammation is usually chronic and less likely to cause the acute, severe symptoms and systemic signs seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ludwig\u0027s angina is primarily caused by the rapid and extensive spread of polymicrobial infection from the floor of the mouth or dental structures into the submandibular and sublingual spaces.","Urgent management, including airway support if necessary, is required in Ludwig\u0027s angina."],"references":["Pak S, Cha D, Meyer C, Dee C, Fershko A. Ludwig\u0027s Angina. Cureus. 2017 Aug 21;9(8):e1588. doi: 10.7759/cureus.1588. PMID: 29062620; PMCID: PMC5650252.","Dowdy RAE, Emam HA, Cornelius BW. Ludwig\u0027s Angina: Anesthetic Management. Anesth Prog. 2019 Summer;66(2):103-110. doi: 10.2344/anpr-66-01-13. PMID: 31184944; PMCID: PMC6560692.","Bridwell, R., Gottlieb, M., Koyfman, A., \u0026 Long, B. (2021). Diagnosis and management of Ludwig\u2019s angina: An evidence-based review. The American Journal of Emergency Medicine, 41, 1\u20135. doi:10.1016/j.ajem.2020.12.030","Acute odontogenic infections. Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13565"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T18:05:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T18:05:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6183"}},"con